Architects have understood that offices also need childcare
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would say that he also hides inside a small nursery with all of his own to such facilities: walls of colors, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outside terrace.
Since October last year, the children of the employees of Arch.Design can come to her.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, whose studio came out numerous well-known buildings in Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-guard.
About 90 people work in the company, mainly at the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, the nursery is one of the benefits that Arch.Design to his workers in the framework of his social program.
Constructors and architects in this way have the possibility of combining a demanding profession with the care of children.
The mini-guard was an idea of the employees themselves of Arch.Designu and, with the support of the management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-guard is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme on Human Resources and Employment, as well as the Czech State budget.
Thanks to funding (an allocation of more than 2.8 million Czech krona) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified personnel and services.
When the financing is exhausted (two years), Arch.Design is obliged to maintain the mini-guardia with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and in the submission of the request for funding contributed the Economy Rating company.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified staff; moreover, a nurse and a teacher of the Ministry of Education are present all day, and the nursery is currently home to children with no age limit, although most of them are less than three years old.
Since this is a "mini-garde", it can only receive a maximum of five children simultaneously, even if the shifts are more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to adapt to the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although this is individual education and care, the contents of the mini-guards programme are comparable to the usual pre-school education programme.
In it children not only play, but also receive quality education: from basic learning to preparation for school, they teach up to English.
The class has not only toys and table games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the sign companies that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program reinforced the marketing of staff.
The bone house remains fascinating after 100 years. Watch Gaudí's interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remind the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, of the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its shape similar to a skeleton, the locals nicknamed it "the house of the bones".
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the innovative use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade that reminds the scales and omnipresent lines gently curved, all of this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
By paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm, and order is observed carefully.
At night, the entire facade of the house seems even more impressive, as it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentia and the twist of forms continue to surprise us also inside.
The corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, the rails, the ornaments of the doors, the mirrors and the signs.
The Casa Batlló, which is located in Eixample district in number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gràcia, arose from the refurbishment of a house in the year 1877 of architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on overthrowing the former building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, did not draw Antoni Gaudí alone.
In the design, architect Josep María Jujol collaborated.
In fact, in their plans of the project there were ornaments for the apartment representative of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade.
In the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the House Milan and the Park Güell of Gaudí, in which there are other pieces of it.
Because of its organic form, the locals soon after its completion nicknamed it "the house of the bones".
Others, due to the specific window opening mechanism, began to call it the "house of the woods".
It is also said that, at the height of the construction, appears the sword of San Jorge, patron of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
It may seem strange its inclination of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí completely failed to respect the construction standards of the moment and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction had obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although, of course, the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so impacted by the result that it requested correction.
He was upset, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather on the contrary: only fifteen days after the request for the city council, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery of the second floor there was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The house, with six floors, is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all the angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the salons and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí's reconstruction, won not only a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and swallows.
The game with the two colors brings the maximum light on all the floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which, on the contrary, absorb sunlight.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment of the accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits, they confirmed, or discovered, that it was a very beneficial business and expanded the visits to the common area and the buhardilla, including the roof terrace.
The price of entry to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and tourist card holders get 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the entry price of other Gaudí constructions in the city.
