A longer index finger than the annular indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men with the longest rate that annular is subject to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the startling conclusion of a study published on Wednesday in a British journal on cancer.
They could depend on testosterone level, male hormone.
"Our results indicate that the relative finger length can be a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, particularly for men up to 60 years of age," said the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, professor of the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
Therefore, the finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, in particular if this characteristic is associated with a genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, Eeles says.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed up with a British counterpart of over 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and, at the same time, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the shortest indica finger of the right hand.
They had the same odds of suffering prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were of the same length.
In the case of men with a longer rate than the annular finger, this risk was reduced by 33 per cent; for men below 60 per cent, the reduction reached 87 per cent.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the matrix.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies indicated that testosterone affects the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he knows the study, but that it does not seem to him that the relationship between finger length and cancer can be "extremely demonstrated".
