Support for democracy in Latin America continues to grow, as well as support for private companies.
Crime generates greater concern than unemployment.
Moreover, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a country more influential than the United States.
These are some of the findings of the last Latinobarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
As the survey has been regularly conducted since 1995, it is possible to monitor changes in attitudes in the region.
The results of this year's survey, held in September and early October, highlight two related issues.
The first is the relatively lively mood reigning in Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in several countries on the Pacific Coast of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6 per cent annually since 2002, democracy support has increased from a reduced of 40 per cent in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
It also grew up in Mexico, where the economy recovered after a major decline in production last year.
However, only half of the respondents from Mexico and Brazil, the two most populated countries in the area, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Figure 2).
About 44 per cent of respondents in the region expressed satisfaction with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but considerably more than 25 per cent registered in 2001 (Graph 3).
About 34 per cent said they trusted the Congress of their country and 45 per cent in their Government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but considerably higher in relation to 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turbulence in Latin America seriously affected the support of democracy.
The fact that it was maintained during the global financial crisis was likely due to the fact that many Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
Furthermore, the existence of a stronger social security network has helped to protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty only marginally increased in 2009 and that it has been reduced again this year, to 32 per cent.)
However, the mood varies considerably from country to country (see Figure 4).
The good economic performance of Brazil and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
That feeling is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the start of the surveys, more polled in Latin America mention crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem their country faces (see Figure 5).
About 31 per cent claims that, whether they or a close relative, they have been victims of crime in the past year, a figure that has been reduced since 38 per cent of last year and that is the lowest percentage since 1995.
The most positive economic performance is reflected in increased support for private companies and the market economy: about 71 per cent of respondents in the region claim that private enterprises are essential for development, while in 2007 only 56 per cent (see Figure 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow your country to develop, compared to 47% last year.
It is interesting that 62% of respondents in Venezuela feel the same way (and 80% supports private companies), although its leftist president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country that exercises greater leadership in the region, as indicated by 19 per cent of respondents (compared to 18 per cent last year), followed by the United States (9 per cent, same as last year) and Venezuela (9 per cent compared to 11 per cent a year ago).
However, the United States is considered the country most influential by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds this title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
