An arsenic-resistant microbe poses the possibility of new forms of life on Earth... or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients broadens the possibility of finding new forms of life on Earth and possibly on other planets.
Although researchers discovered the curious bacteria here on Earth, they say they demonstrate that there may be life forms without the main elements they considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity."
"It can grow either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"That makes it very peculiar, although little is lacking to be a truly 'alien' type of life," said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report appearing in the online Thursday edition of the Science publication.
For a long time, there have been six major elements essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
However, researchers have discovered that the bacteria, found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus by arsenic.
"It makes you think what else is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
Anbar said that finding is important for the search for life on planets other than Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the call for a press conference to discuss it, in which no details of the discovery were disclosed, generated a great speculation on the Internet about the possibility of the report indicating the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery "yes shows is that in other planetary environments, there could be organisms that use other elements to drive their biochemistry and that the set of "stand" elements that we consider indispensable for life may not be so fixed," said Charles Cockell, Professor of Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is novel because it demonstrates the replacement of one element by another in biochemistry and the basic biochemical structure," Cockell added.
The discovery was not by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon from NASA Astrobiology Institute, who conducted the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so it speculated that one microbe exposed to both could replace one another.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus."
"It can therefore be difficult for organisms to differentiate them."
"However, the arsenic is different enough so that it doesn't work as well as the phosphorus, so it enters and, by some means, calls the biochemical machinery," explains Anbar.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, to which they managed to adapt and use to grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus, but showing that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that there may be a natural way of life that uses arsenic, either in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where the arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, indicated that the idea that arsenic can be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but an example had never been found to prove it works.
The arsenic was more common in the early ages of the earth, he noted, so researchers speculated that the first forms of life may have used it.
"Yes, it suggests that there could be other means of generating life, not just the way life was formed on Earth long ago," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Health Institutes.
