Senator's lawyers announced on Wednesday that the prosecutors of the Department of Justice have apologized to Senator John Ensign for the criminal charges that arose from their affair with a former campaign assistant and their efforts to secure lobby work for the woman's husband.
The decision ends with the most serious legal threat facing Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered as possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012, until the scandal over his business had national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Ensign's office said he felt "certainly happy" about the decision, which came after an entire year's investigation.
The senator could still face a disciplinary measure of the Senate's ethics committee.
Ensign's lawyers said that the Department of Justice had "informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer an objective of his investigation and that he has no plan to raise charges against him on this matter."
The Department of Justice did not want to comment on the case.
The announcement was a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, who said there seemed to be significant evidence to indicate that Ensign might have confabulated to violate a federal criminal lobby ban.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents that were first released in October 2009 in the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to get lucrative work through lobby, to achieve the silence of Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, on the Senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as a treasurer for an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find work for Mr. Hampton and advocated on their behalf after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby them, according to the documents and interviews.
Since Hampton had recently been an assistant to Ensign, he was excluded according to the law of lobbying for his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethical experts said that the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, appeared in disagreement with the so-called "revolving door lobbying ban", which seeks to restrict former state employees using their connections to do personal business.
From the evidence that has been made public, "it appeared to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the revolving door status," said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients investigated by the government.
While the Department of Justice officials refused to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the department seemed cautious in accepting political proceedings after several major setbacks to its public integrity section, including last year's decision to abandon the prosecution against former Senator Ted Stevens, in the midst of charges for misconduct.
Federal prosecutors "are clearly cowards," said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defense group that brought several complaints against Ensign in the case.
"This basically means high-ranking government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them," he added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign's principal lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a prosecutor from the Department of Justice on Monday and another call the following day, telling him that the department did not want to raise charges against his client.
Ensign's defence team had been cooperating with prosecutors in an attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law."
Coggins refused to explain in detail the legal arguments he gave to prosecutors.
"I don't feel comfortable entering into details about my discussions with the Justice Department, I can only say that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to change an investigation into a complaint separated by the ethics group, claiming that a payment of 96,000 dollars from Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated the federal electoral law.
The electoral commission said it had no evidence to prove that the money was just a gift.
NV Energy is an important Nevada company that had long supported the senator, who got work through lobby thanks to Ensign's help to Hampton.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that after the company accepted Hampton as lobbyist, Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Hampton and told him he was "maching" the Ministry of the Interior on a matter of dispute.
Ensign also attended a lunch with Hampton and another customer from Nevada, Allegiant Air, and called on the transport secretary to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after he had hired Hampton to lobby.
When the news of the affair first appeared last year, Ensign apologized to his constituents and renounced his position as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
