Can civics hold a bridge to unite the divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invetivity and negativity this week has triggered a bit of civicism in Washington.
Is it a pretense of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
The Tuesday meeting between President Obama and the leaders of Congress made no progress on the major issues to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But as everyone says, it was at least a polite discussion of the differences of both sides, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to win partisan points.
The President's deficit commission's public meeting on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that remain among the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is barely enough to state that a new era of cooperation has come.
Both sides are now in a trial period, testing each other to identify signs of co-operativeism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
The reason why the meeting on Tuesday and subsequent assessments of the meeting by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and are very deeply rooted to suggest any rapid change in the climate that existed over the last two years.
Whether it is tax, expenditure, health care or social assistance, the two sides are in opposite poles.
However, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed with respect to the way things are said," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Centre for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They are inevitable after the elections.
Elections arouse partisan passions, which then fade away.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing meeting, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts are won at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment subsidies, probably because the Republicans cannot make them believe they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, denying unemployment subsidies for the unemployed.
After the Tuesday meeting in the White House, there is greater optimism for possible treatment of these issues during the outgoing session, together with the ratification of the new START Nuclear Disarmament Pact (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty).
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warns that successful cooperation in the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continuous bipartisanism when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
On the contrary, he stated that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement should begin.
"After the things to be done are carried out in the short term, psychology will reverse the situation to a confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed scepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civicism can lead to genuine cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a trial for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters of Tea Party, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know that they must try to fulfill their promises to cut the state's expenses and cancel the new health law.
These lines of support are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include reform of the tax code and the increase in some taxes and retirement age, and the cut in expenditure.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have been responsible for one of the most difficult work in Washington and, according to their own assessment, the issue of the deficit on the public agenda has been brought to force in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the officers elected in the panel, suggesting that there are at least now few bases or wishes for commitment on fiscal matters.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the White House Republicans and those of Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of partisan shocks, when Republicans challenge Obama about the budget, taxes and medical assistance, followed by a period of increased bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the people.
Anyone who thinks he's losing will probably change course and look for compromise.
However, this can be an optimistic vision.
Partyism and polarization are now greater than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and Congress Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization that is shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common points on issues that still divide them.
