In June 2006, following a report by the Council of Europe accusing of complicity in practices contrary to human rights to a dozen countries, including Spain, a meeting took place between former US Ambassador Eduardo Aguirre and Fernández de la Vega.
The Vice-President recognized that the Council's report "has taken the Zapatero Government out of play" and insisted that Spain had nothing to hide in this matter.
"From Vega he stressed that Spain has no repairs to intelligence flights through Spanish territory."
"They just want to be informed" to avoid being caught off guard," reports Aguirre on a cable.
Also the then foreign holder, Miguel Ángel Moratinos, pointed out to the ambassador that the Spanish executive "wanted to give this matter the lowest possible profile, although, by being in the hands of the judges, the Government had limited capacity to influence."
For his part, in January 2007, Prosecutor Vicente González transmitted to the Embassy that he would not try to block the judge's initiative to request the declassification of the documents of the National Intelligence Centre (CNI) and the Department of Defense on CIA flights.
"These reports contain no criminality or sensitive information," the Embassy explained after speaking to the prosecutor.
However, the US reflected its concern about the "apparent coordination between the Spanish judge and the German prosecutors" rather than the disclaimed information of the CNI or the Ministry of Defence.
"This coordination among independent investigators will complicate our efforts to handle the case discreetly between governments," regrets Aguirre.
In March 2007, at a lunch between the U.S. ambassador and the Minister of the Interior, Alfredo Pérez Rubalcaba, he told him that "although the Spanish judges are rabidly jealous of their independence and will do what they consider appropriate," he had instructed his collaborators "to avoid remarks of inflamed rhetoric, in an attempt to lower the temperature."
The Ambassador also expresses his concern about the PP's action on this matter.
"Despite its general pro-American orientation, our experience suggests that the PP will not hesitate to capitalise on any indication that the Zapatero Government has tolerated or deliberately ignored US actions that could be interpreted as possible human rights violations, even if these revelations have negative consequences for the U.S. Government," he says.
