This is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German put on the market in 2007 for far-reaching purposes away from the high automotive competition.
Named PLM, this powerful computer tool has been used to design assembly chains of manufacturing factories worldwide, power plants, high precision instruments.
The goal is to play, simulate faithfully the product or process before building it in a real way, thus avoiding errors and avoidable expenses.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi planes or Nissan's most famous utilitarian cars.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of the industrial division of Siemens, explains that the use of this computer instrument at its Formula 1 factory has allowed Red Bull to design and carry out "in a few hours, almost in real time", the modifications, changes and improvements detected during the races and in the trials.
Russwurm explains that the Squires in 1992 had an average of 10 technicians on their team who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements to vehicles during each season.
In the Red Bull team today, 180 highly qualified young professionals are working, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyzing and projecting all sorts of modifications in the balloons.
Siemens's manager explained that PLM software is able to analyze and improve all elements of Red Bull's balloons except the engine, which is of Renault's entire responsibility.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are modified.
Changes can be brought from the virtual reality of the simulator to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser production systems and high-tech autoclaves.
As the only limitation of this insanity of technological improvement is the figure of $40 million that each Formula 1 team can spend at most in each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech factory to design and produce its balloons in a town about 50 kilometres from London.
These are two buildings in which visits are restricted, especially for journalists.
Everything that happens there is considered "high-secret."
