I change rules for getting visa
Persons should go to Visa Applicants Service before their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and as well as the waiting time.
From 10 January 2011 it will change the procedure of processing a visa at the United States Embassy and consulates.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants should go to the Visa Applicant Service (ASC) before their interview with the Consular Section.
The CSA staff shall take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer necessary to make a payment to conclude the appointment, another payment to process the visa application, and another payment for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment that will cover the three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases on request (including temporary workers' visas) and $390 for visas from traders and investors.
People wishing to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest CSA where they will present their documents and take their stamps.
Because biometric information will be taken in the AUC, applicants who require a second date to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in this less time than in the past.
Similarly, those applying for visas in the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of 26 dollars.
For additional information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
