A Global Plan for Renewal of Lighting
Yesterday, the UN has proposed in Cancún a renewal plan for domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in one hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GEI) in an amount that is almost one third of the additional decrease to be made to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of major specific projects that the UN expects to take in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, even better, by light bulbs of electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LED" in English), much of the 1.800 million tonnes (Gt) of GHG issued on the planet would be avoided to illuminate humans.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions from the planetary motor park.
In Copenhagen, last year, large issuing countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, were committed to voluntary reduction plans that were expected to decrease global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of that quantity should be reduced to stabilise, by 2020, the two-degree temperature increase in order to prevent it from being decommissioned.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluocompact bulbs, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, energy consumption is further reduced twice as much.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, like those that the manufacturer Philips has launched this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, allowing us to get an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in one hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also work with reostates and emit very little heat.
Above that, they contain nothing of mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluocompact bulbs, since they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers place instructions.
However, the report indicates, the main source of mercury emission on the planet is not the fluocompact bulbs, but the thermal coal plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that is spilled with the incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these power stations emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the advantages that this international programme would offer each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save one billion dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, i.e., the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power stations whose construction would cost it 2.5 billion.
