Avenger hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it unveils an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous in the face of hypocrisy governing relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and provides for a future dominated by regression.
But let's step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirmation of the fact that each file created by a secret service (independent of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and the sinisterly ridiculous profile of Khadafi has been giving Cabaret artists ideas for creating their sketches for a long time.
The rule that secret files should only be formed by news of public knowledge is essential for the dynamics of secret services, and not just in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that every work repeats (about the Grial, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to the occult not only trust what they already know, which confirms what they have already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is fearful, just as he is fearful (or has little anxiety) the head of the secret services (if he could not be, I know, editor of the Liberation), which only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sending the U.S. embassy from Rome to the State Department was the same as the newsweek published the previous week.
Why, then, have the revelations of these files caused such a revolt?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, i.e. that embassies, at least since World War II and since Heads of States can call by phone or catch the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic role and, with the exception of some limited exercises of representation, have become spy centres.
Any viewer who sees research films knows perfectly, just pretend we don't know it because of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a poor image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that a hacker anyone can consult the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world has a significant impact on the prestige of the State Department.
The scandal therefore affects both the victims and the "greens".
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
Formerly, in Orwell's time, he could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true since he was able to control every move thanks to the phone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen became a complete victim of the power eye.
But when it is shown, as is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can one stand a power that can no longer keep his own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be unveiled); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but revealing, as WikiLeaks has done, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means taking away all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information into the network, as it would be like publishing it in a street poster.
But it is also clear that, with current technologies, confidential telephone conversations cannot be expected.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a Head of State has moved by plane and contacted one of the counterparts.
How can they maintain private and confidential relations in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my prediction is a matter of science fiction and therefore novelism, but I imagine government agents moving discreetly in due course with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, like much, hiding some data written in the heels of their shoes.
This information is then preserved, in a single copy, in locked drawers: in the end, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is now advancing like a crab, that is, backward.
A century after the cableless telegraph has revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a telegraph with cables (telephones).
Video tapes (analogs) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, discovering all the secrets of the assembly, while now the CDs (digitals) only allow to move forward or back from chapter to chapter, i.e. to enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travels it takes, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing unusual for politics and communication techniques to take us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was secretly happening at the embassies.
Currently, it is the embassies who request confidential information from the press.
Climate: French hats in their funding pledges
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unblocked funding promises (called fast start or early) made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French hats have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged to contribute EUR 7.2 billion in three years and EUR 1.260 million in France (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of leaflets...
The transparent operation was appreciable and was appreciated for what is really worth: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2010 €2.2 billion, which sets it on the right path towards fulfilling its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each one chooses the best reference.
For example, the European Commission has taken as a reference the year 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added in three years as fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" of the year 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to expenditure in previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even shrink), while it intends to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the distribution of donations and loans.
Again, there is no standard and each one chooses the method of calculation.
Some, such as France, believe that each euro provided is equivalent to one euro donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
While the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often, projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is meant to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... As a matter of fact, only the cost of the loan for the country granting the loan should be calculated for its commitments (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France does not find such reasoning useful: "respect" its commitment of EUR 420 million by making 91.5 % of loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (EUR 36.1 million); see the EU document for its own eyes.
This is the only Union country that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it in 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union provides a euro to fulfil its commitment, France only provides 10 cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
That's a good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France has double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions in time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
By spending only EUR 36.1 million, it can give the impression that it costs 420 million "new and additional", as promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has taken over arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why were the other Member States still giving when they can just lend?) and in the negotiations, since developing countries are not dumb...
The chapter on early funding is a relatively short-term statement in relation to all climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra sand grain in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it doesn't.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, especially, France could make progress in the discussions on bets at stake in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is with others.
So we have the hope of the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancún next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of the "additional character" and the use of loans would help improve the level of international confidence needed to advance the negotiations.
